  "_setup_notes": [
    "REBUILT after a live error: n8n 2.8.4's Code node runs in a sandboxed task-runner that does NOT support helpers.httpRequestWithAuthentication -- confirmed by the actual error message. Every network call in this version is now a real HTTP Request node with native credential authentication (unaffected by that sandbox restriction); Code nodes here only do pure JS (base64 decode, frontmatter parsing, string building) -- zero network calls from any Code node.",
    "APPROVAL IS NOT HANDLED BY THIS WORKFLOW ON PURPOSE. Only one workflow can own your bot's Telegram webhook (the existing Inbox workflow) -- adding a second Telegram Trigger here would silently steal it. Approving a draft means telling Claude directly to flip content/queue/<id>.md's status from draft to approved and push. This workflow only watches for status: approved on its schedule.",
    "Create an n8n credential of type 'Twitter OAuth1 API' named EXACTLY 'X API - Meal Prep' using the Consumer Key, Consumer Secret, Access Token, and Access Token Secret from developer.x.com's Keys and Tokens page -- the OAuth 1.0 section specifically, not OAuth 2.0 (Client ID/Client Secret are a different, unused system here). App permissions must be Read and Write BEFORE the Access Token was generated, or posting will fail with a permissions error.",
    "The posting phase (reply-chaining a thread) is a fixed, unrolled chain of up to 12 (IF exists -> post) pairs, not a dynamic loop. This is deliberate: threading requires each tweet's request to reference the PREVIOUS tweet's returned id, a genuine sequential dependency n8n's standard loop node (Split In Batches) isn't built for, and this repo doesn't have live access to verify this n8n version's exact loop/state semantics. A bounded static chain, with each node explicitly wired to the next, is far more predictable to author correctly blind. Current drafts max out at 10 tweets; this leaves 2 slots of headroom. If a future thread needs more than 12 tweets, the 'Pick oldest approved' node will throw a clear error naming the limit -- ask Claude to regenerate the chain with a higher MAX_TWEETS rather than hand-editing the JSON.",
    "THIS STILL NEEDS A LIVE TEST BEFORE YOU TRUST THE SCHEDULE -- now more than before, since this is a substantially different structure than what already failed once. Test by: set one queue file to status: approved, then manually run this workflow once from the n8n editor (it WILL actually post to X, not a dry run) and watch it complete node by node. If any node errors, the error message plus which node it happened on is exactly what to bring back for a fix -- these are usually small, targeted corrections once we know which specific node/expression n8n's version disagrees with.",
    "Set this workflow's Error Workflow (3-dot menu -> Settings -> Error Workflow) to '[Meal Prep] Error Alert -> Telegram', same as your other three workflows (D-050) -- so a failed post reaches Telegram instead of failing silently.",
    "Cadence: every 2 days at 10:00 UTC (cron: 0 10 */2 * *) -- edit the Schedule Trigger node directly in the n8n UI to change it. If nothing is status: approved when it fires, the workflow ends quietly at 'Posted one?' -- not an error.",
    "REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_TELEGRAM_USER_ID in the notify node -- same numeric id used in your other three workflows.",
    "Known limitation, unchanged from before: a partial-thread failure (posts 3 of N tweets, then a later call fails) leaves those live on X and the queue file untouched at status: approved, so the next scheduled run reposts the whole thread from tweet 1. If the error alert ever fires mid-thread, check the account and manually delete the orphaned partial thread before the next run."
  ]
